</td><td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">There is an agreed time (based on patient preference) for the medication to be taken. Up to three SMS reminders are sent to the patient on the day of medication, depending on whether the patient replies or not. These reminders are sent at the agreed time medication is to be taken and subsequently at 12 noon and 6 <sc>p.m.</sc> if no reply is received. SMS text is &#x0201c;please take the medication on time&#x0201d; and is the same for each reminder. The patient is expected to reply by SMS with or without text. Once a reply has been received, the reminders stop for that day.</td><td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">SMS reminder sent 4, 3, 2, and 1 d before the scheduled monthly follow-up visit.</td><td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Adherence patterns based on patient interview, pill count from medication monitor box, and SMS feedback. <break/>Recommended that: <break/>&#x02022; If 3&#x02013;6 doses were missed, patient is switched &#x0201c;intensive management&#x0201d;, in which village/community doctors visited the patient once a week for the rest of treatment; <break/>&#x02022; If &#x02265;7 doses were missed or 3&#x02013;6 doses missed in 2 mo, patient is switched to DOT, with each dose of treatment supervised by the village/community doctor. <break/>Incentives (5 RMB/patient visit) were paid to village/community doctors<xref rid="t001fn002" ref-type="table-fn">
<sup>2</sup>
</xref> for intensive management of non-adherent patients.</td></tr><tr><td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">
